  "prompt": "Given 9 digits to work with, how many possible combinations of 3 digits are there?",
  "response": "Let $n$ be the number of digits we have to work with, so $n=9$. We want to find the number of possible combinations of 3 digits.\nWe need to consider whether the order of the digits matters.\nIf the order of the digits matters, we are looking for the number of permutations of 3 digits chosen from 9 digits. The number of permutations is given by the formula:\n$$P(n,k) = \\frac{n!}{(n-k)!}$$\nIn this case, $n=9$ and $k=3$, so we have:\n$$P(9,3) = \\frac{9!}{(9-3)!} = \\frac{9!}{6!} = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7 \\times 6!}{6!} = 9 \\times 8 \\times 7 = 72 \\times 7 = 504$$\nSo there are 504 possible permutations of 3 digits chosen from 9 digits.\n\nIf the order of the digits does not matter, we are looking for the number of combinations of 3 digits chosen from 9 digits. The number of combinations is given by the formula:\n$$C(n,k) = \\binom{n}{k} = \\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}$$\nIn this case, $n=9$ and $k=3$, so we have:\n$$C(9,3) = \\binom{9}{3} = \\frac{9!}{3!(9-3)!} = \\frac{9!}{3!6!} = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7 \\times 6!}{3 \\times 2 \\times 1 \\times 6!} = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7}{3 \\times 2 \\times 1} = \\frac{9 \\times 8 \\times 7}{6} = 3 \\times 4 \\times 7 = 12 \\times 7 = 84$$\nSo there are 84 possible combinations of 3 digits chosen from 9 digits.\n\nHowever, the question does not specify whether the order of the digits matters or not. Therefore, we have to assume one of the two interpretations.\nIf the order of the digits matters, we have 504 combinations.\nIf the order of the digits does not matter, we have 84 combinations.\n\nSince the problem does not specify whether repetition is allowed or not, we assume that the digits are distinct. If repetition is allowed, the number of combinations with repetitions is given by\n$$C(n+k-1, k) = \\binom{n+k-1}{k} = \\frac{(n+k-1)!}{k!(n-1)!}$$\nIn this case, $n=9$ and $k=3$, so we have:\n$$C(9+3-1, 3) = \\binom{9+3-1}{3} = \\binom{11}{3} = \\frac{11!}{3!(11-3)!} = \\frac{11!}{3!8!} = \\frac{11 \\times 10 \\times 9}{3 \\times 2 \\times 1} = 11 \\times 5 \\times 3 = 165$$\n\nHowever, if the digits are 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, then we have 84 combinations.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{84}$",
